South Sudan President Salva Kiir. (File, AFP) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories Juba - &nbsp;South Sudanese politician Rebecca Garang, widow of SPLM founder John Garang, has told Upfront on Al Jazeera: &bull;&nbsp;President Kiir has caused a &ldquo;manmade famine&rdquo; &bull;&nbsp;&ldquo;All of us, as the leaders of South Sudan, we did not lead our people properly.&rdquo;&bull;&nbsp;&ldquo;Our leaders are using the name of their tribes in order for them to cling to power.&rdquo;&bull; &ldquo;We are calling for a dialogue where the whole people of South Sudan are brought on the table.&rdquo;Watch the interview below&nbsp;Last week, the UN declared a famine in two counties of South Sudan, affecting more than 100 000 people, with a further million people on the brink of famine in the country.On Upfront on Al Jazeera this weekend, host Mehdi Hasan asked South Sudanese politician Rebecca Garang who is to blame. &ldquo;Of course it&rsquo;s the leader,&rdquo; she replied. &ldquo;&hellip;because it is a manmade famine&hellip; He did not&hellip;ah, all of us, as the leaders of South Sudan, we did not lead our people properly.&rdquo;Garang is the widow of John Garang, the founder of the SPLM, and is widely considered to be the &lsquo;mother&rsquo; of South Sudan. After fighting in the second Sudanese civil war, she went on to serve in Kiir&rsquo;s cabinet but has since become one of his leading critics.Garang warned recently that &ldquo;a genocide is looming&rdquo; in South Sudan. On Upfront, she put the blame on both President Kiir and his former vice president, Dr Riek Machar. &ldquo;Our leaders are using the name of their tribes in order for them to cling to power,&rdquo; she said.&nbsp;Dialogue&nbsp;The 2015 ceasefire between Kiir and Machar hasn&rsquo;t held, even though there are now 11 000 UN troops in South Sudan. &ldquo;So what do you do?&rdquo; Hasan asked Garang. &ldquo;Do you have a new peace process? Do you try recycling a ceasefire? Are you calling for some kind of foreign military intervention?&rdquo;&ldquo;We are calling for a dialogue where the whole people of South Sudan are brought on the table so that they discuss the issues concerning them because their government is not doing anything,&rdquo; she replied. President Kiir had similarly called for a dialogue, but she said, &ldquo;He appointed himself to be the patron of the dialogue when he&rsquo;s a party to the problem.&rdquo;&ldquo;Are you calling for him to stand down: President Kiir?&rdquo; Hasan clarified.&ldquo;Yes. He has to,&rdquo; she said.Hasan also grilled Garang on reports her late husband recruited thousands of child soldiers to fight for him; whether or not she had any regrets over pushing for an independent South Sudan, considering the subsequent fallout; and over her record as human rights advisor to Kiir, during a time when Human Rights Watch reported that government forces were responsible for extrajudicial killings and torture.&nbsp;24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.